{"questionId":"25884","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider the function&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msqrt><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></msqrt></math>, where&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>2</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The curve <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is rotated <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>π</mi></math> about the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math>-axis to form a solid of revolution that is used to&nbsp;model a water container.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Show that the volume, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mtext>m</mtext><mn>3</mn></msup></math>, of water in the container when it is filled to a height&nbsp;of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math> metres is given by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>π</mi><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>h</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>h</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>attempt to substitute&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></msqrt></math>&nbsp;into&nbsp;the correct volume formula&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>π</mi><munderover><mo>∫</mo><mn>0</mn><mi>h</mi></munderover><msup><mfenced><msqrt><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></msqrt></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>d</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mi>π</mi><munderover><mo>∫</mo><mn>0</mn><mi>h</mi></munderover><mfenced><mrow><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>d</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>π</mi><msubsup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>0</mn><mi>h</mi></msubsup></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>π</mi><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>h</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>h</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong><br>Note:</strong> Award marks as appropriate for correct work using a different variable e.g.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>π</mi><munderover><mo>∫</mo><mn>0</mn><mi>h</mi></munderover><msup><mfenced><msqrt><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></msqrt></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></math></p>\n<p><em><strong><br>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"25884","referenceCode":"22M.2.AHL.TZ1.10c.i","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Show that the volume, V m3, of water in the container when it is filled to a height of h metres is given by V=π13h3+h.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"c.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.17—Areas under curve onto y-axis, volume of revolution (about x and y axes)"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}